"""
mkt-context layer — Acts chapters 27–28
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/acts.json
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-acts-27-28.py
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: Merge new verse entries without overwriting already-present keys — safe to re-run.
    # CHANGE? If commentary JSON structure changes from {ch:{v:html}}, update this traversal.
    # VERIFY: Re-running the script should produce identical output (no duplicate or overwritten entries).
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ACTS_CH = {
"27": {
"1": "<p>The decision to sail to Italy places Paul under the custody of Julius, a centurion of the Augustan Cohort (speira Sebastē). A cohort (speira) was nominally 480–600 soldiers; the Augustan Cohort was a special unit stationed in the eastern provinces, attested in inscriptions as handling administrative and escort duties between Rome and the provinces. Julius's consistently respectful treatment of Paul (vv. 3, 43) distinguishes him from the hostile magistrates of the narrative.</p>",
"2": "<p>The Adramyttian ship (ploi Adramyttēnō) was a coastal vessel from Adramyttium, a port in the Troad (northwest Asia Minor). Such a vessel would sail the coastal route, stopping at Asian ports — not a direct Italy-bound ship. The plan was to transfer at a suitable Levantine or Asian port to a vessel bound for Italy. Aristarchus of Thessalonica (one of the seven collection delegates, Acts 20:4; cf. Col 4:10; Phlm 24) travels as Paul's companion — his continued presence through the voyage and into Rome reflects the dedicated companionship of Paul's co-workers.</p>",
"3": "<p>Sidon was the major Phoenician port city immediately north of Tyre on the Lebanese coast — a natural first stop from Caesarea. Julius allows Paul to 'go to his friends and receive care' (epitimeleias tychein) — a remarkable allowance suggesting either official permission or a degree of informal trust built between the centurion and Paul during the journey from Caesarea. The Sidonian Christian community, of unknown origin in Acts, hosts Paul briefly.</p>",
"4": "<p>The voyage 'under the lee of Cyprus' (hypepleusamen tēn Kypron) — sailing on the sheltered eastern side of the island to avoid the prevailing northwest summer winds that made direct sailing westward difficult. The Etesian winds (summer northwest winds in the Mediterranean, modern meltemi) created predictable headwinds for westbound traffic, forcing vessels to take indirect, sheltered routes. The choice to go north of Cyprus rather than south reflects competent seamanship.</p>",
"5": "<p>The voyage 'across the sea along Cilicia and Pamphylia' traversed the southern coast of Asia Minor — the route familiar from Paul's first journey (Acts 13:13–14). Myra in Lycia was a major port of the southern Lycian coast (modern Demre, Turkey) and a key node in the Alexandrian-to-Rome grain trade. The Egyptian grain fleet frequently called at Myra to pick up favorable winds for the run to Italy, making it a natural transfer point from a coastal vessel to a grain ship.</p>",
"6": "<p>The Alexandrian grain ship (ploi Alexandrinō) was an enormous merchant vessel carrying Egyptian grain to Rome — the lifeblood of Roman food supply. Egypt produced approximately one-third of Rome's grain, and the state-organized grain fleet (annona) was critical infrastructure. Josephus describes similar voyages (Life 3); Lucian's satirical dialogue The Ship describes an Alexandrian grain ship sheltering at Piraeus as 180 feet long with 600 passengers — an approximate scale for ships of this class. Julius's ability to commandeer space on such a vessel reflects his official authority.</p>",
"7": "<p>The slow progress over 'many days' to reach Cnidus (the southwestern tip of Asia Minor) reflects the difficulty of westbound summer sailing against the Etesian winds. Cnidus was a major city and naval base; the inability to make headway there forced the ship to take shelter under the lee of Crete — sailing south of the island to shelter from the northwest winds. Cape Salmone was the eastern promontory of Crete.</p>",
"8": "<p>Fair Havens (Kalous Limenas) is a small bay on the southern coast of Crete near the city of Lasea — the site is identified with the modern Limenes, confirmed by the nearby town of Lasaia in inscriptions. The harbor provided reasonable shelter but was considered inadequate for winter anchorage — the decision about whether to winter there or push on to the larger harbor at Phoenix (Phoinixa) was the crux of the dangerous debate in vv. 10–12.</p>",
"9": "<p>'The Fast' (hē nēsteia) was Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement — the only fast mandated in the Torah (Lev 16:29; 23:27). It falls on 10 Tishri (September-October in the Gregorian calendar), marking the end of the safe sailing season. Ancient meteorological wisdom divided the year into navigational seasons: safe (May–September), risky (March–May; September–November), and dangerous (November–March). The Fast falling in late September or October signaled that the ship was already in dangerous territory and should winter.</p>",
"10": "<p>Paul's warning — 'I can see that the voyage is going to be disastrous and bring great loss to ship and cargo, and to our own lives also' — was based on either prophetic insight, practical sailing knowledge, or both. Paul had already been shipwrecked three times (2 Cor 11:25) and was an experienced sea traveler. His use of 'I perceive' (theōrō) — an observation verb rather than a prophetic formula — may indicate practical assessment, with the subsequent angel vision (v. 23) adding divine confirmation.</p>",
"11": "<p>The centurion defers to the 'captain' (kybernētē — literally steersman/navigator) and 'ship's owner' (nauklērō) over Paul's warning. In Roman merchant shipping, the naúklēros was the ship owner or operator who bore financial responsibility for the cargo; the kybernētēs was the professional navigator. Their professional judgment that pushing on was feasible outweighed the prisoner's advice — a reasonable decision within the parameters of their responsibility, though ultimately wrong.</p>",
"12": "<p>Phoenix (Phoinixa) was a Cretan harbor facing southwest and northwest — a more sheltered winter anchorage than Fair Havens. The majority vote (hoi pleiones) to push on reflects ship's council decision-making in antiquity — crew, officers, passengers, and cargo interests all had stakes in the decision. The harbor has been identified with various locations on the southern Cretan coast; its exact identification remains debated among historical geographers.</p>",
"13": "<p>A gentle south wind (notos) seemed to confirm the decision to leave — the deceptive calm that sets up the disaster. The south wind allowed them to sail close along the Cretan coast toward Phoenix — a short, apparently manageable coastal run that would have been routine in good conditions. The crew's confidence (doüntes tēs protheseos kekratēkenai — thinking they had obtained what they wanted) is the psychological setup for the reversal.</p>",
"14": "<p>The Euraquilo (Eurakylōn) — a hybrid Greek-Latin name combining Euros (east wind) and Aquilo (Latin: north wind) — was a violent northeasterly storm, the ancient equivalent of a northeaster. Modern meteorologists identify it with the gregale, a violent northeast wind that strikes without warning in the central Mediterranean, particularly between Malta and Crete. It struck before the ship could complete the coastal run and gain the shelter of Phoenix.</p>",
"15": "<p>The ship was 'caught' (synarpasthentes — seized, snatched away) and 'unable to face the wind' (antophthalmein tō anemō — literally 'look the wind in the eye') — a technical term for a ship unable to hold its course against wind. Running before a strong northeasterly would drive the vessel southwest toward the Libyan coast and its dangerous shallows (the Syrtis). The decision to 'give way and be driven' (epidontes epherometha) was the standard seamanship response to a storm that outmatched the ship's ability to tack.</p>",
"16": "<p>Cauda (Gauda — modern Gavdos, south of Crete) provided brief shelter on its lee side, allowing the crew to manage the skiff (skaphē) — the small boat towed behind or secured on deck, which had been swamped by the storm. The difficulty in securing the skiff ('we were barely able to get control of the ship's boat') indicates the sea conditions were already violent. Cauda is the southernmost point of Europe and provided the last shelter before open water.</p>",
"17": "<p>Three emergency measures: (1) hoisting the skiff on deck; (2) 'undergirding' the ship (hypozōnnyntes tēn naus — frapping, passing ropes under the hull and over the deck to prevent the planks from opening in heavy seas — a technique described in ancient sources); (3) lowering the gear (to skeuos) — probably the mainsail and yard, reducing windage to a bare minimum. The fear of the Syrtis (hē Syrtis — the sandbars of the Greater and Lesser Syrtis on the Libyan coast) was a mariner's nightmare in antiquity, notorious as a ship-swallowing graveyard.</p>",
"18": "<p>The 'violent storm' (cheimazomenōn) drove the ship beyond human control. The first day's jettisoning (ekbolēn epoiounto) of cargo was a standard maritime response — lightening the ship to reduce draft and improve seakeeping. The ekbolē (cargo jettison) appears in ancient maritime law (Digest 14.2.1 — the Rhodian Sea Law) as a recognized emergency measure that created communal liability for losses. The cargo was Egyptian grain — an enormous financial loss for the naúklēros and investors.</p>",
"19": "<p>The second day's jettisoning of the ship's 'tackle' (skeuē — equipment, probably including spare spars, rigging, and heavy gear) with their own hands indicates that every available person was working to save the vessel. The distinction from v. 18 (cargo jettisoned by crew) to v. 19 (tackle thrown 'with our own hands' — Luke and Paul's party joining the effort) marks the escalation to crisis requiring all hands. The loss of spare gear meant the ship was now committed to arriving or sinking.</p>",
"20": "<p>No sun or stars for 'many days' meant no celestial navigation — the ship's position was unknown. Ancient Mediterranean navigation depended entirely on celestial observation and coastal landmarks; under overcast storm conditions, navigators were essentially blind. 'No small storm' (cheimonos ouk oligou) is Lukan understatement — the storm had erased the crew's ability to determine where they were or where they were going. The 'all hope of being saved was abandoned' (periaireisthai elpis pasa) sets the stage for Paul's reversal of despair.</p>",
"21": "<p>Paul's speech — after 'much abstinence' (asitias, probably referring to the inability to cook in storm conditions) — combines 'I told you so' with renewed hope. The reminder of his warning in v. 10 is not self-congratulation but authority-building: if his previous assessment was accurate, his new message (vv. 22–26) deserves credence. The rhetorical strategy of establishing prophetic credibility before delivering a new oracle is standard in ancient speech conventions.</p>",
"22": "<p>Paul's promise — 'there will be no loss of life, but only of the ship' — inverts the expected outcome. The promise of life preservation while accepting ship-loss gives the crew a specific, credible, and practically actionable promise: stop despairing, start managing the ship for a controlled disaster. The source of this confidence is given explicitly in the next verse — divine revelation, not maritime optimism.</p>",
"23": "<p>The angel of 'the God to whom I belong and whom I worship' (tou theou hou eimi kai hō latreuō) — Paul's self-identification as God's servant creates the authority chain: this is not Paul's personal assessment but a message from the God who governs both Paul's life and the outcomes of events. The phrasing echoes OT theophany language where the angel speaks for the divine principal (cf. Gen 16:7–13; Exod 3:2). The night apparition (v. 23, implied by the storm conditions) follows the pattern of Paul's other nocturnal visions (16:9; 18:9; 23:11).</p>",
"24": "<p>'Do not be afraid, Paul; you must stand before Caesar' — the divine assurance recapitulates the commissioning of Acts 23:11 ('you must also testify in Rome'). The 'must' (dei) is the divine necessity governing the entire Jerusalem-Rome narrative. God has given Paul 'all those who sail with you' — the 276 passengers and crew are beneficiaries of Paul's presence and divine purpose, a remarkable claim that grounds communal salvation in prophetic mission.</p>",
"25": "<p>'Therefore take heart, men, for I have faith in God that it will be exactly as I have been told' — Paul's faith statement before the crew. The shift from 'I told you so' (v. 21) to 'I believe God' (pisteuō tō theō) marks the theological center of the speech: Paul's confidence is not in his own judgment but in divine fidelity. The speech functions as an acted sermon — 14 days of storm will test whether Paul's God delivers what he promised.</p>",
"26": "<p>'But we must run aground on some island' — the specific prediction of shipwreck on an island rather than open-sea loss (drowning all) gives the crew actionable information: navigate toward land when possible. The prediction is both honest (the ship will be lost) and hope-giving (on an island, not in the deep). Its specific accuracy — Malta rather than Libya — confirmed after the fact demonstrates the reliability of the prophetic source.</p>",
"27": "<p>'The fourteenth night' of the storm indicates they had been driven by the Euraquilo for two weeks — carried approximately from Crete to the central Mediterranean. 'Adria' (tō Hadria) in the ancient sense was broader than the modern Adriatic Sea, encompassing the central Mediterranean including the Ionian and Sicilian waters. Modern calculations of storm-driven drift over 14 days from Crete confirm that Malta would be a plausible landfall for a vessel driven southwest. The sailors 'suspected land' (hypōn oun prosagein tina autois chōran) — perhaps hearing breakers or seeing changes in wave pattern.</p>",
"28": "<p>Soundings (bolisantes) using a lead-line (bolida — a weighted cord with depth markings) were the standard navigation technique near land in antiquity. Twenty fathoms (orgyas eikosi — approximately 36 meters) decreasing to fifteen fathoms as they sounded again indicates shallow water ahead — approaching land. The depth profile recorded here has been matched by modern soundings of the approaches to Malta's St. Paul's Bay, providing one of the most specific geographical confirmations in Acts.</p>",
"29": "<p>'Fearing we might run on the rocks' — the crew's rational response to shoaling water at night in unknown territory was to anchor and wait for daylight. Dropping four anchors from the stern (ek prumnēs) rather than the bow was a specific technique that kept the ship's bow pointed toward the beach for eventual beaching — a deliberate seamanship choice, not mere panic anchoring. The 'wishing for day' (euchoumenoi hēmeran genesthai) captures the anxious vigil of experienced sailors who know they are close to land but cannot see where.</p>",
"30": "<p>The sailors' attempt to escape by pretending to lay anchors from the bow while actually lowering the skiff exposes a crew-abandonment scheme — leaving passengers and soldiers on an unmanageable vessel. The conflict between self-preservation and duty was acute: professional sailors would have known they could swim to shore; non-swimmers (most soldiers and passengers) would be at the mercy of the ship. Paul's identification of the scheme ('if these men do not stay in the ship, you cannot be saved') demonstrates both his observation skills and his understanding that divine promise operates through human means.</p>",
"31": "<p>Paul's words to the centurion and soldiers — 'unless these men stay in the ship, you cannot be saved' — are theologically significant: God's promise of universal salvation (v. 24) does not eliminate the necessity of the sailors' professional presence. Providence and human agency cooperate; the divine guarantee of survival does not make seamanship irrelevant. Julius responds immediately by having the soldiers cut the skiff's ropes, eliminating the escape option and keeping the sailors aboard.</p>",
"32": "<p>The soldiers cut the ropes of the skiff (ta schoiniai tēs skaphēs apekopsan) — destroying the vessel's only lifeboat. This act of apparently irrational destruction (from a self-preservation standpoint) was an act of trust in Paul's word and, behind it, in the God who gave it. The action also effectively committed everyone to the ship's fate — no one could quietly slip away. The solidarity forced by this decision mirrors the communal trust required for Paul's God to be vindicated.</p>",
"33": "<p>Paul urges everyone to eat — fourteen days without proper food (asitoi diatetelekate — 'you have remained without food') in the physical and psychological stress of a continuous storm. The phrase 'without food' may reflect inability to cook in storm conditions, rationing, or loss of appetite through terror. 'This is for your survival' (pros tēs humetereas sōtērias hyparchei) — Paul frames eating as mission-critical, a practical means to the survival God has promised.</p>",
"34": "<p>'Not a hair is to perish from the head of any of you' (thriks apo tēs kephalēs oudenos apolesetai) echoes the divine promise formula in 1 Samuel 14:45 (Jonathan's rescue: 'not one hair of his head shall fall to the ground'), Luke 12:7 ('the hairs of your head are all numbered'), and Luke 21:18 ('not a hair of your head will perish'). The idiom from Jesus's eschatological discourse is applied literally to the shipwreck situation — Luke may be drawing a deliberate allusion to Jesus's words as fulfilled through Paul's prophetic ministry.</p>",
"35": "<p>Paul's taking of bread, giving thanks to God in the presence of all (eucharistēsen tō theō enantion pantōn), breaking, and beginning to eat follows the standard form of Jewish table grace and early Christian Eucharistic practice. The action is not the Eucharist in the technical sense — the 276 people are not a Christian community — but the form (take, give thanks, break, eat) is the same sequence used in the feeding miracles (Matt 14:19) and the Lord's Supper (Luke 22:19; 1 Cor 11:23–24). The public thanksgiving is itself a missionary act — an act of trust in God before 276 witnesses.</p>",
"36": "<p>'All of them were encouraged and ate food themselves' (esthion kai autoi) — the communal meal shifts the atmosphere from despair to renewed purpose. The pragmatic psychology of feeding a starving, terrified crew before asking them to perform the demanding work of beaching the ship is sound; Paul's theological framing gives the meal a significance beyond mere nutrition. The entire complement joins in, making Paul's thanksgiving a communal act of trust in the God he worships.</p>",
"37": "<p>'There were two hundred and seventy-six of us in the ship' — the specific number, included in some manuscripts as 'about seventy-six' in others, provides a historically concrete headcount. Alexandrian grain ships of this class could carry several hundred people; Josephus describes traveling on a ship that sank with 600 aboard (Life 3 — he survived by swimming). The number 276 functions as a narrative accountability marker: the promise that all would be saved will be verified by the count in v. 44.</p>",
"38": "<p>The final jettisoning of the wheat (ton siton) lightened the ship maximally for the beaching attempt. The grain cargo — the ship's entire commercial purpose and financial value — was thrown into the sea as the last act of preparation for survival. The progressive stripping of the ship across the voyage (cargo in v. 18, tackle in v. 19, now the remaining grain) tracks the total loss Paul had predicted (v. 10) while all life is preserved as he promised (v. 22).</p>",
"39": "<p>At daybreak the crew saw an unknown coast with a bay having a beach (aigialon — sandy shore rather than rocky cliff) — the crucial feature for a controlled beaching. The identification of the bay as modern St. Paul's Bay on Malta's northeastern coast has been made on geographical and navigational grounds, though archaeological confirmation remains elusive. The crew's decision to beach the ship rather than anchor and wait (dangerous in the continuing swell) was the professional judgment call that translated Paul's promise into practical action.</p>",
"40": "<p>The beaching procedure: (1) cut the anchor ropes (abandoning four anchors to the sea floor); (2) loosen the rudder lashings — large Mediterranean merchant ships had two steering oars (rudders) lashed amidships in heavy weather, now released for steering; (3) hoist the foresail (artemon) to drive the ship onto the beach. The technical precision of this description confirms Luke's eyewitness source — these specific nautical actions are consistent with ancient Greek and Roman seamanship practice.</p>",
"41": "<p>The ship runs aground on a place of 'two seas' (topos dithalassos) — a sandbar or reef between two channels, where the bow struck fast and held while the stern broke up from the surf. The exact feature has been identified with various formations in St. Paul's Bay. The bow's immovable grounding and the stern's violent destruction by the waves is the specific disaster pattern: the ship splits between fixed and mobile ends, making orderly disembarkation impossible.</p>",
"42": "<p>The soldiers' plan to kill the prisoners (kteinas tous desmiotas) was standard Roman procedure when prisoners might escape — a soldier who allowed a prisoner to escape faced the same punishment as the escaped prisoner (typically death, cf. Acts 12:19; 16:27). Julius overrides the plan specifically for Paul's sake ('wanting to bring Paul safely through') — the centurion's personal commitment to Paul's survival supersedes institutional protocol, a remarkable prioritization that costs the soldiers their escape insurance.</p>",
"43": "<p>The ordered disembarkation: swimmers first, then those on planks and pieces of the ship. The sequence ensures the strongest swimmers reach shore to assist the non-swimmers; the wreckage becomes improvised floatation. Luke's 'we' presence in these verses (implied by the first-person context) makes this an eyewitness account of the evacuation. The narrative's deliberate accounting — everyone makes it — sets up the fulfillment of Paul's prophecy.</p>",
"44": "<p>'In this way it happened that they all escaped safely to land' (pantes diesōthēsan epi tēn gēn) — the fulfillment of the divine promise (v. 24: 'God has granted you all those who sail with you'). The verb diasōzō (to bring safely through) is the narrative's theological conclusion: God's saving power operates through storm and shipwreck, through sailors and soldiers, through jettisoned cargo and improvised floatation, to bring every soul safely to land. The geography has changed from Judea to Malta; the missionary journey has entered its final phase."
},
"28": {
"2": "<p>The 'native people' (hoi barbaroi) of Malta — the term barbaros simply means non-Greek-speaker, not savage or uncivilized, in classical usage. Malta's population was predominantly Punic (Phoenician-rooted), speaking a Semitic language that was neither Greek nor Latin. The Maltese spoke a language related to ancient Phoenician; the island had been part of the Carthaginian sphere before Rome took it in 218 BC. Their 'unusual kindness' (ou tēn tychōsan philanthrōpian) — extraordinary hospitality by any standard — is noted without condescension.</p>",
"3": "<p>Paul gathers brushwood (phryganōn ti plēthos) and places it on a fire — participating in the practical work of the survivors' camp rather than holding aloof as a prisoner. A viper (echidna) comes out from the heat of the fire and fastens to his hand. Malta is snake-free today (no venomous snakes are native), which has generated scholarly debate about the identification of the island — some propose the Dalmatian island Mljet. Most scholars maintain Malta and allow either that a species has since died out or that Luke's 'echidna' was a nonvenomous snake perceived as dangerous by the Maltese.</p>",
"4": "<p>The Maltese interpretation — 'No doubt this man is a murderer; though he has escaped from the sea, Justice has not allowed him to live' — invokes the personification of Justice (Dikē) common in Greek popular religion. The inference is logical within their worldview: a man who survives a shipwreck only to be bitten by a snake must be under divine retribution for some hidden crime. The word dike (justice) had both the abstract and personal meanings — as a goddess of moral order who pursues the guilty through circumstance and accident.</p>",
"5": "<p>Paul 'shook off the creature into the fire and suffered no ill effects' (oudèn kakon epathen) — the promised preservation ('not a hair of your head will perish,' 27:34) extended beyond the shipwreck to the subsequent snake encounter. The casual, unhurried response ('shook off') contrasts with the crowd's expectation of dramatic collapse. The connection to Jesus's promise in Luke 10:19 ('I have given you authority to tread on serpents') and Mark 16:18 ('they will pick up serpents') places Paul in the chain of those upon whom this dominical authority operates.</p>",
"6": "<p>The Maltese watch for symptoms — swelling (pimprастhai — to swell, typically from venom) or sudden death (katapiptein — falling down suddenly) — and when neither comes, they reverse their verdict from 'murderer' (phoneus) to 'a god' (theon einai). The oscillation between 'murderer' and 'god' mirrors the crowd reaction at Lystra (Acts 14:11–19), where Paul was first hailed as Hermes and then stoned. Popular religion's interpretation of extraordinary events in theological categories — crime-punishment or divine-presence — is the common framework Paul consistently redirects toward the living God.</p>",
"7": "<p>Publius — 'the leading man of the island' (tō prōtō tēs nēsou) — bore a title confirmed by two Maltese inscriptions using the Greek prōtos and the Latin primus, attesting that 'first man' was the actual official designation for the chief Roman authority on the island (either the island's governor or the chief magistrate). His three-day hospitality for Paul and his companions was expensive generosity on behalf of 276 survivors — a significant act of philoxenia (hospitality to strangers) that Luke notes before the healing that follows.</p>",
"8": "<p>Publius's father suffered from fever and dysentery (pyretois kai dysenteriō). The combination of 'fevers' (plural, pyretois) and dysentery has led medical historians to identify the condition with Malta fever (brucellosis), caused by the Brucella melitensis bacterium endemic in Maltese goats and transmitted through unpasteurized goat's milk. The disease was formally described in 1887 by Sir David Bruce after studying Maltese patients; it remained common on the island until the 20th century. Paul's healing — entering, praying, laying on hands — echoes Jesus's healing method (Mark 1:41; Luke 4:40).</p>",
"9": "<p>The chain reaction of healings — 'the rest of the people on the island who had diseases came and were cured' (etherapeuonto) — uses a different verb from v. 8 (where iasato — healed definitively). The plural and the different verb may indicate both miraculous healing and ordinary medical care (Luke the physician's contribution). Luke does not specify that these healings were in the name of Jesus — the context implies it, but the narrative focus is the divine power operating through Paul rather than an explicit evangelistic proclamation.</p>",
"10": "<p>The Maltese 'honored us with many honors' (pollais timais etimēsan hēmas) and provided supplies (ta pros tēn chreian) for the onward voyage — material gifts that translated the reciprocal hospitality obligation into practical support for the mission. The three months (v. 11) on Malta gave Paul's party time to recover, the community to form, and the ship to be reprovisioned. Luke does not record the establishment of a Maltese church, though Christian tradition holds it dates from this visit.</p>",
"11": "<p>The ship wintering at Malta was another Alexandrian grain ship — the route from Alexandria to Rome involved wintering at intermediate ports. Its figurehead (parasēmō) depicted Castor and Pollux (Dioskouroi — the divine twins of Greek mythology), patron deities of navigation and protectors of sailors. Their cult was pervasive in Mediterranean seafaring communities; Poseidon/Neptune's sons in mythology, they were associated with the electrical phenomenon called St. Elmo's fire, seen as their presence during storms. The ship name and figurehead provide precise historical texture.</p>",
"12": "<p>Syracuse was the major city of Sicily — once the greatest Greek colony in the western Mediterranean, still a major port in the Roman period. The three-day stop allowed provisioning and possibly a connecting cargo pickup. The coastal route from Syracuse north to Rhegium (modern Reggio Calabria, the toe of Italy) then northwest to Puteoli was the standard approach to the Italian mainland for vessels coming from the east and south.</p>",
"13": "<p>Puteoli (modern Pozzuoli, near Naples) was the primary Roman grain port in the first century — the main harbor serving the capital before Claudius's development of Ostia. The Alexandrian grain fleet regularly arrived at Puteoli; the port infrastructure (docks, warehouses, commercial districts) was geared to the grain trade. The discovery of a Christian community there ('found brothers and sisters') suggests the Puteolan church had been established perhaps a decade earlier — by traders, freedpersons, or members of the Alexandrian Jewish diaspora.</p>",
"14": "<p>The week's stay at Puteoli — 'We found brothers and sisters and were invited to stay with them for seven days' — required Julius's permission, suggesting the centurion continued his pattern of accommodation toward Paul. Paul would have used the week for pastoral work with the Puteolan community, news-gathering about Rome, and possibly writing. The week's delay before the final 200 km journey to Rome on foot also allowed advance notice of Paul's approach to reach the Roman community.</p>",
"15": "<p>The Roman Christians came out to meet Paul at the Forum of Appius (Foron Appiou — 43 Roman miles from Rome, on the Appian Way) and Three Taverns (Treis Tabernas — 33 Roman miles from Rome). The Appian Way (Via Appia) was the main southern highway entering Rome, running from Capua through the Pontine Marshes to Rome. The Forum of Appius was a market town and canal-boat terminus in the Pontine region; Three Taverns was a smaller posting station. The advancing delegation of believers meeting Paul echoes the Thessalonian imagery of the parousia in 1 Thessalonians 4:17 (apantēsis — a formal civic welcome for a dignitary approaching the city).</p>",
"16": "<p>In Rome Paul is allowed to 'stay by himself, with the soldier who guarded him' (kathʼ heauton ... syn tō phylassontī auton stratiōtē) — a relatively relaxed form of custody called custodia militaris, where the prisoner was chained to a soldier but not confined to prison. This arrangement allowed receiving visitors, conducting meetings, and presumably writing letters (cf. Phil 1:13; Col 4:3, 18; Phlm 1 — all written from Roman imprisonment). The relatively open custody reflects the lack of a formal criminal charge: Paul was accused by the Sanhedrin but had committed no Roman crime (25:25; 26:31–32).</p>",
"17": "<p>Paul's first action in Rome is to call together 'the local leaders of the Jews' (tous ontas tōn Ioudaiōn prōtous) — the synagogue presidents of Rome's Jewish community. The Roman Jewish community was substantial — estimates range from 20,000 to 50,000 persons in the first century, with multiple synagogues in different districts (Trastevere, Ostia, the Subura). Paul's initiative to meet Jews first rather than Gentiles is consistent with his principle ('to the Jew first,' Rom 1:16) and avoids the appearance that he had come to Rome as a troublemaker who had burned his Jewish bridges.</p>",
"18": "<p>Paul's summary of his case to the Roman Jews — arrested by Jerusalem Jews, examined by Romans, found innocent (mēdemian aitian), proposed to be released — matches the Lukan narrative of Acts 22–26 compressed into a diplomatic opening statement. The repeated motif of Roman authorities finding no capital charge (23:29; 25:25; 26:31) reaches its final articulation here: Paul himself reports the Roman verdict of innocence to the community that will witness his appeal to Caesar.</p>",
"19": "<p>Paul's explanation that he was 'compelled to appeal to Caesar' (anagkasthēn ... epikalesasthai Kaisara) frames the appeal not as aggression against his people but as self-defense: 'not that I had any charge to bring against my nation.' The appeal to Caesar (Acts 25:11) was a Roman citizen's right that Paul exercised to escape the Sanhedrin's lethal intent — not to prosecute Israel. This diplomatic framing serves both to reassure the Roman Jews and to model the mission's non-aggressive relationship to Judaism as a people.</p>",
"20": "<p>Paul's final phrase — 'it is because of the hope of Israel that I am wearing this chain' — crystallizes his theological self-understanding. The 'hope of Israel' (hē elpis tou Israēl) is the resurrection and the Messianic fulfillment — the hope Paul argues for in every defense speech (23:6; 24:15; 26:6–7). His chains are not a badge of shame but a consequence of defending Israel's own scriptures and promises. The statement invites the Roman Jews to see Paul not as a traitor to Israel but as Israel's defender before a hostile world.</p>",
"21": "<p>The Roman Jews disclaim any letters from Judea about Paul and any negative reports from visitors — a historical detail that puzzles some scholars (one might expect the Sanhedrin to have corresponded with Rome's Jewish community about Paul). The disclaimer may reflect genuine ignorance (Festus had handled the appeal quickly without prior consultation), or diplomatic caution (the Roman Jews preferred to hear Paul directly rather than prejudge based on second-hand reports). Their offer to hear his views demonstrates the relative openness of the Roman community to Paul's message at this point.</p>",
"22": "<p>'The sect that is everywhere spoken against' (hē hairesis autē ... antilegomenon) — the Roman Jews' characterization of Christianity as a 'sect' (hairesis — the same term used for Sadducees in Acts 5:17 and Pharisees in 15:5 and 26:5) reflects outsider language. The sect is everywhere 'spoken against' (antilegomenon) — the pattern of opposition documented throughout Acts is here acknowledged by the Roman Jewish leadership as a known phenomenon. Their curiosity about 'your views' (ti phroneis) frames the subsequent encounter as a genuine inquiry rather than a predetermined judgment.</p>",
"23": "<p>The 'great number' of visitors to Paul's lodging spend from morning to evening hearing his testimony about the kingdom of God — an extended theological seminar, not a brief talk. Paul's method: 'testifying to the kingdom of God, and trying to convince them about Jesus both from the Law of Moses and from the Prophets.' The dual reference (Torah + Prophets) reflects the whole-canon hermeneutic of Paul's missionary preaching (cf. Acts 17:2–3; 26:22–23; Luke 24:27, 44). This final exposition to Roman Jews recapitulates the entire Lukan kerygmatic method in a single scene.</p>",
"24": "<p>The divided response — 'some were convinced, but others disbelieved' (hoi men epeithonto, hoi de ēpistoun) — is the consistent pattern of Paul's synagogue missions throughout Acts (13:43–45; 14:1–4; 17:4–5; 18:4–8; 19:9). The division within the Roman Jewish community between believers and disbelievers enacts the prophecy Paul is about to quote — Isaiah 6's warning of partial response to divine proclamation. The mixed response is not failure but fulfillment of the prophetic pattern.</p>",
"25": "<p>'Disagreeing among themselves' (asymphōnoi ontes pros allēlous) — the internal division among the Jewish visitors becomes the occasion for Paul's parting word. 'The Holy Spirit was right in saying to your ancestors through Isaiah the prophet' — attributing Isaiah 6 to the Spirit rather than to God directly (cf. Acts 1:16; 4:25; Heb 3:7; 10:15) is consistent with early Christian pneumatology that understood the prophets as Spirit-inspired. The attribution bridges First Temple prophecy and present reality through the Spirit's continuous voice.</p>",
"26": "<p>The Isaiah 6:9–10 citation — 'hearing you will hear but not understand; seeing you will see but not perceive' — was already central to the Gospel tradition (Mark 4:12; Matt 13:14–15; Luke 8:10; John 12:40). Isaiah 6 describes the hardening effect of the divine word on those who are called but resist — the message that saves the receptive hardens the resistant. Luke's citation is the longest Isaiah 6:9–10 quotation in the NT (following the LXX), using it as the theological explanation for Jewish rejection of the gospel throughout Acts.</p>",
"27": "<p>The Isaiah quotation continues — 'For this people's heart has grown dull, and with their ears they can barely hear, and their eyes they have closed; lest they should see with their eyes and hear with their ears and understand with their heart and turn, and I would heal them.' The three organ/function pairs (heart-understand, ears-hear, eyes-see) capture the comprehensive nature of the hardening. The conditional clause — 'lest they should ... turn, and I would heal them' — preserves God's willingness to heal if the condition of turning were met: the hardening is not absolute but conditional on continued resistance.</p>",
"28": "<p>'Therefore let it be known to you that this salvation of God has been sent to the Gentiles; they will listen' (autoi kai akousontai) — the pivot from Jewish rejection to Gentile reception that has been the structural engine of Acts since 13:46 ('we are turning to the Gentiles'). The 'they will listen' is not triumphalist exclusion of Jews but a statement of missionary direction given ongoing Jewish resistance in each location. Paul's ministry at Rome continues (vv. 30–31) with 'all who came to him' — including Jews — but the Isaiah quotation marks the theological conclusion of the Acts narrative's synagogue mission arc.</p>",
"29": "<p>Verse 29 ('And after he had said these things, the Jews departed, having much dispute among themselves') is absent from the earliest and best manuscripts (P74, Sinaiticus, Alexandrinus, Vaticanus) and appears to be a later scribal addition harmonizing with the pattern of Paul's synagogue departures throughout Acts. Most modern textual critics consider it secondary.</p>",
"31": "<p>'Proclaiming the kingdom of God and teaching about the Lord Jesus Christ with all boldness and without hindrance' (meta pasēs parrēsias, akōlytōs) — the final word of Acts is akōlytōs, 'without hindrance.' The word is a legal term: the Roman system has not, despite two years, produced a verdict against Paul. The irony is the book's concluding note: the empire that arrested Paul cannot stop the message Paul proclaims. 'Without hindrance' closes the narrative that began with the outpouring of the Spirit and the commission to go to 'the ends of the earth' (1:8) — Rome being the symbolic end point, the center of the world from which the word radiates outward. The open ending (Paul in Roman custody awaiting trial) is Luke's deliberate conclusion: the mission continues beyond what Acts can record."
}
}

